Please enter a search term. Peyton Kennedy joined News 2 in November 2022 as a reporter for Good Morning Nashville. She comes to Tennessee after working as a multimedia journalist, fill-in anchor, and weather person for Nexstar’s CBS affiliate, WTAJ News, covering Central Pennsylvania from Altoona & State College. Peyton’s stories at WTAJ earned her three honors, including Best Feature Story (Keystone Media Awards) and Outstanding Spot News Coverage (Keystone Media Awards & Pennsylvania Association of Broadcasters Awards). She is a proud 2020 graduate of the James Madison University Honors College in Harrisonburg, Virginia, where she double-majored in Journalism & Theatre Performance and double-minored in Entrepreneurship & Honors Leadership Studies. She also served as a member of the Student Government Association & was a sister of Delta Delta Delta. While at JMU, Peyton was the co-anchor for the university’s live, weekly newscast Breeze TV, where she also founded and anchored the show’s entertainment segment. She was honored to receive the Virginia Press Women Foundation Agnes Cooke Scholarship, the Alison Parker Memorial Scholarship, and Lisanby Scholarship for her dedication to journalism and the arts. During the summer of 2019, Peyton studied with the JMU in Los Angeles program, where she held internships in reality television development (Kinetic Content), documentary film production (Atlas Films), and talent management (AEFH Talent Agency). You could spot her having fun as a seat filler at award shows and television tapings on weekends! Peyton is a New Jersey native and is thrilled to join the Music City community. When not in the newsroom, Peyton enjoys supporting the arts, exploring local parks on walks, cheering on the Dukes, and diving into the area’s vibrant country music scene! She is passionate about meaningful and impactful storytelling. If you have a story idea, or want to say “howdy”, please don’t hesitate to send Peyton a message here!'}]

(WMC) - After nearly three decades in broadcast journalism, and nearly two decades in Memphis, Action News 5′s Kontji Anthony has decided to step away from the anchor desk. Kontji has spent the last 17 years serving the Mid-South community, telling your stories and sharing first-hand how much she loves Memphis and the Mid-South. She began her broadcasting career at the age of 17 as a host for her high school television station. In the years that followed, she worked for TV stations in New York, Missouri, California and North Carolina before making her way to Memphis and WMC. Kontji says her time at Action News 5 has been enriching, but after 28 years in the business, “it is time for me to take a new direction.” “I leave Action News 5 with deep appreciation for my coworkers and fond memories of the many extraordinary relationships cultivated throughout the years that are forever etched in my heart,” she said. Kontji adds, “I also cherish my deep love for the great people of the Mid-South who allowed me to sit next to The Joe Birch, Ron Childers and Jarvis Greer, welcoming me into their homes for nearly two decades.” We’re sad to lose Kontji as part of the Action News 5 team, but we’re excited to see what she does next. Kontji will continue anchoring the 5, 6 and 10 p.m. newscasts through mid-April. Copyright 2022 WMC. All rights reserved. Click here to sign up for our newsletter!
